s and insight into the nature of reality.</p><p>The Bodhisattva principle exemplifies the dynamic relationship between care and insight. It emphasizes that intelligence is not solely about controlling causal chains to achieve predetermined goals, but it highlights the element of spontaneity that arises in the interplay of object, agent, and action. According to Buddhist analysis, the perception of a separate, enduring, and controlling self is considered illusory and epiphenomenal. Recognizing the interdependent and constructed nature of object, agent, and action leads to the realization of their emptiness or lack of inherent existence. This deconstruction of apparent cognitive foundations brings about a transformation in the cognitive system of a Bodhisattva, expanding their field of affordances and engendering care for all apparent individuals.</p><p>From the perspective of a cognitive system that is not deeply informed by insight into no-self, personal selfhood is reified, and one's own well-being and flourishing take precedence. However, for a Bodhisattva, the perception of a self deserving special care extends equally to all sentient beings. The understanding of no-self accompanies the perception that all individuals, oneself included, share the same ultimate identity and are equally deserving of care and compassion.</p><p>Overall, in the Buddhist framework, care is intricately connected to the recognition of no-self and the cultivation of intelligence that transcends self-centeredness, leading to a compassionate orientation towards all beings.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http: